item.title: Turning the tide on China’s dominance of the rare earth market is possible. Here’s what it would take
item.description: Creating a supply chain elsewhere is ‘humanly possible’ but requires ‘some real strategery,’ USA Rare Earth’s CEO said at the recent World Changing Ideas Summit. Rare earth minerals are so ubiquitous and critical to much of today’s technology, that tonight’s dinner might not have made it to the table without them. And according to USA Rare Earth CEO Barbara Humpton, for decades, the world has sat back and let China become the sole supplier of these minerals, even as the country has used its dominance in this market as a geopolitical game piece....

item.title: This busy NYC neighborhood just got way more walkable
item.description: Downtown Brooklyn’s congested streetscapes are now pedestrian friendly. Here’s how simple improvements made a boring street great. Like many American cities, the streetscape in downtown Brooklyn was for a long time very heavy on the street: a great place to park a car or drive through. But over the past 20 years, the area itself has gone from being a 9-to-5 shopping and business district to one where a growing number of people live 24-7. Since 2004, more than 22,000 housing units have been added to the neighborhood, changing its character so much that its old streetscape just wasn’t cutting it...
